org.beryx.streamplify.example

Class Fibonacci

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.beryx.streamplify.LongIndexedSpliterator<BigInteger,Fibonacci>
      • org.beryx.streamplify.example.Fibonacci
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Spliterator<BigInteger>, Streamable<BigInteger,Fibonacci>

    public class Fibonacci
extends LongIndexedSpliterator<BigInteger,Fibonacci>
    Provides Fibonacci numbers in a given interval of indices as a stream of BigInteger.
    The implementation illustrates the use of a LongIndexedSpliterator and the construction of its value supplier.
    The Fibonacci.Supplier.apply(long) method computes the Fibonacci number with the index given by its argument as follows:
    • if the requested index is the successor of the previously computed index, it uses the recurrence formula: F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)
    • otherwise, it uses the formula:
      F(2*k) = F(k) * (2 * F(k+1) - F(k))
      F(2*k+1) = F(k+1)^2 + F(k)^2
    It is also possible to compute the Fibonacci number with a given index by using the closed-form solution given by Binet's formula (see Fibonacci.Supplier.forIndexBinet(int)). However, this involves time consuming BigDecimal computations, leading to situations where using a parallel stream takes longer than using a sequential one. (See Jacobsthal for an example of a series with computationally cheap closed-form solutions.)
